P(B\mid A)=1-\varepsilon
0<\varepsilon<1
P(C\mid B)=1
P(C\mid A)â‰¥1-\varepsilon
P(C\mid B)=1
P(B \cap C)=P(B)
P(B)=P(B\cap C)
\begin{align} P(B\cap A)&=P(B)-P(B\cap A^c)\\ &=P(B\cap C)-P(B\cap A^c)\\ &\leq P(B\cap C)-P(C\cap B\cap A^c)=P(B\cap C \cap A)\\ &\leq P(C\cap A). \end{align}
 P(B\mid A)=1-\epsilon\leq P(C\mid A). 
